pr_body:
The workspace for the VF2++ implementation. This PR only exists so people can take a look at our work, provide feedback and discuss about the implementation. It is only a draft and is not meant to be merged yet.

The related milestone and issues can be [found here](https://github.com/kpetridis24/networkx/milestone/1)

Python's `for` command can have an `else` clause which is run when the loop finishes normally (without a `break` statement).  Not every user knows about for/else so you want to make sure it is more readable than not using it.  Perhaps something like the following, but you should decide which is more readable:
```python
for nbr in G1[popped_node1]:
    if nbr in mapping:
        T1.add(popped_node1)
        break
else:  # no neighbors in the mapping
    T1_out.add(popped_node1)
```
Here's another form which might or might not be more readable:  (Note that `any` stops the loop when it finds a value that is True just like the `break` syntax does.)
```python
if any(nbr in mapping for nbr in G1[popped_node1]):
    T1.add(popped_node1)
else:
    T1_out.add(popped_node1)
```
And an even shorter, but probably harder to read:
```python
(T1 if any(nbr in mapping for nbr in G1[popped_node1]) else T1_old).add(popped_node1)

For example, what should happen when one (or both) of the input graphs have no nodes?

Some basic tests for this case might look something like:

```suggestion

def test_both_graphs_empty():
    G = nx.Graph()
    H = nx.Graph()
    assert isomorphic_VF2pp(G, H, {}, {})


def test_first_graph_empty():
    G = nx.Graph()
    H = nx.Graph([(0, 1)])
    assert not isomorphic_VF2pp(G, H, {}, {})


def test_second_graph_empty():
    G = nx.Graph([(0, 1)])
    H = nx.Graph()
    assert not isomorphic_VF2pp(G, H, {}, {})
```

These cases might seem extremely basic and even redundant, but simple checks like these form the basis of good, comprehensive unit testing! Note also that I've implicitly made some choices about behavior above; i.e. that two null graphs are isomorphic and any non-null graph is *not* isomorphic to a null graph. Is this correct? Or are some of these (i.e. null to null) pointless concepts? I'm not really sure, but tests like this help frame the discussion for these corner cases and will end up codifying the behavior!

This particular example highlights why writing tests early in the design process can be extremely valuable, as it forces you to think about what the behavior *should* be for common inputs - you can then write the code so that the test cases pass.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 7, 14, 11, 8, 18, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'rossbar', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 922432271, 'comment_body': 'Thanks a lot for your time and valuable information!     if not G1.is_directed():
